</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="301" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="301">Note.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="301">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Olivier" authorityYear="1791" class="Insecta" family="Dryopidae" genus="Dryops" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Dryops" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="301" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="301">Dryops</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a worldwide distribution and comprises 79 species (
<bibRefCitation author="Shepard, WD" journalOrPublisher="Natural History Bulletin of the Siam Society" pageId="0" pageNumber="301" pagination="89 - 126" publicationUrl="https://thesiamsociety.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/NHBSS_061_2e_ShepardSites_Aquatic.pdf" refId="B92" refString="Shepard, WD, Sites, RW, 2016. Aquatic beetles of the families Dryopidae and Elmidae (Insecta: Coleoptera: Byrrhoidea), of Thailandia: Annoted list and illustrated key to genera. Natural History Bulletin of the Siam Society 61 (2): 89 - 126, https://thesiamsociety.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/NHBSS_061_2e_ShepardSites_Aquatic.pdf" title="Aquatic beetles of the families Dryopidae and Elmidae (Insecta: Coleoptera: Byrrhoidea), of Thailandia: Annoted list and illustrated key to genera." url="https://thesiamsociety.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/NHBSS_061_2e_ShepardSites_Aquatic.pdf" volume="61" year="2016">Shepard and Sites 2016</bibRefCitation>
), three of them are recorded from Mexico.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="301" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="301">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="301">
Mexico (Chiapas, Morelos), Belize, Costa Rica (
<bibRefCitation author="Burgos, SA" editor="Navarrete-Heredia, JL" journalOrPublisher="Universidad de Guadalajara y Universidad Autonoma del Estado de Morelos, Guadalajara" pageId="0" pageNumber="301" pagination="69 - 95" refId="B26" refString="Burgos, SA, Trejo-Loyo, AG, 2001. Lista preliminar de los coleopteros registrados para el estado de Morelos, Mexico. In: Navarrete-Heredia, JL, Fierro-Lopez, HE, Burgos-Solorio, A, Eds., Topicos sobre Coleoptera de Mexico. Universidad de Guadalajara y Universidad Autonoma del Estado de Morelos, Guadalajara: 69 - 95" title="Lista preliminar de los coleopteros registrados para el estado de Morelos, Mexico." volumeTitle="Topicos sobre Coleoptera de Mexico." year="2001">Burgos and Trejo-Loyo 2001</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Shepard, WD" journalOrPublisher="Pan-Pacific Entomologist" pageId="0" pageNumber="301" pagination="53 - 59" refId="B90" refString="Shepard, WD, 2004. Lotic regions of Belize and their aquatic Byrrhoid Coleoptera (Dryopidae, Elmidae, Lutrochidae, Psephenidae, Ptilodactylidae). Pan-Pacific Entomologist 80 (1-4): 53 - 59" title="Lotic regions of Belize and their aquatic Byrrhoid Coleoptera (Dryopidae, Elmidae, Lutrochidae, Psephenidae, Ptilodactylidae)." volume="80" year="2004">Shepard 2004</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1649/0010-065X-71.3.437" author="Barr, CB" journalOrPublisher="The Coleopterists Bulletin" pageId="0" pageNumber="301" pagination="437 - 444" refId="B16" refString="Barr, CB, Shepard, WD, 2017. Eubria mesoamericana Barr and Shepard (Coleoptera: Psephenidae: Eubriinae), a new psephenid species from Central America with an enigmatic generic distribution. The Coleopterists Bulletin 71 (3): 437 - 444, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1649/0010-065X-71.3.437" title="Eubria mesoamericana Barr and Shepard (Coleoptera: Psephenidae: Eubriinae), a new psephenid species from Central America with an enigmatic generic distribution." url="https://doi.org/10.1649/0010-065X-71.3.437" volume="71" year="2017">Barr and Shepard 2017</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.4580.1.1" author="Zaragoza-Caballero, S" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="0" pageNumber="301" pagination="1 - 122" refId="B108" refString="Zaragoza-Caballero, S, Rodriguez-Miron, GM, Vega-Badillo, V, Gonzalez-Ramirez, M, Zurita-Garcia, M, Dominguez-Leon, ED, Lopez-Perez, S, Gutierrez-Carranza, IG, Cifuentes-Ruiz, P, Perez-Hernandez, CX, Ramirez del Valle, E, Gutierrez, NA, 2019. Checklist of the Coleoptera (Insecta) from Morelos, Mexico. Zootaxa 4580 (1): 1 - 122, DOI: https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.4580.1.1" title="Checklist of the Coleoptera (Insecta) from Morelos, Mexico." url="https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.4580.1.1" volume="4580" year="2019">Zaragoza-Caballero et al. 2019</bibRefCitation>
). It has been recorded at an altitudinal range of 200 to 840 m (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1649/0010-065X-71.3.437" author="Barr, CB" journalOrPublisher="The Coleopterists Bulletin" pageId="0" pageNumber="301" pagination="437 - 444" refId="B16" refString="Barr, CB, Shepard, WD, 2017. Eubria mesoamericana Barr and Shepard (Coleoptera: Psephenidae: Eubriinae), a new psephenid species from Central America with an enigmatic generic distribution. The Coleopterists Bulletin 71 (3): 437 - 444, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1649/0010-065X-71.3.437" title="Eubria mesoamericana Barr and Shepard (Coleoptera: Psephenidae: Eubriinae), a new psephenid species from Central America with an enigmatic generic distribution." url="https://doi.org/10.1649/0010-065X-71.3.437" volume="71" year="2017">Barr and Shepard 2017</bibRefCitation>
); in this study 
<taxonomicName genus="D." lsidName="D. mexicanus" pageId="0" pageNumber="301" rank="species" species="mexicanus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="301">D. mexicanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was collected at levels 1 (670 m), 2 (934 m), and 3 (1,126-1,194 m).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="301" type="comments">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="301">Comments.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="301">Collected on substrates consisting of gravel, macrophytes, and leaf packs; found in all sampling months (February 2018 through February 2019, dry and rainy seasons); also collected with a bucket light trap.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
